Finding Possible Ticker Symbols

As were looking at S&P 500 data and plan to cluster the different companies with regard to their performance (and crisis performance) well try to get as many companies, that have been listed in the S&P 500 and exist to this day.

We take all ticker symbols that have been in the S&P 500 since 1996. We use the tracking data supplied in this repository.

s_and_p_movements <- read_csv("data/S&P_500_Historical_Components_and_Changes_2021_25_04.csv")

-- Column specification ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
cols(
  date = col_date(format = ""),
  tickers = col_character()
)

For all these years well collect all symbols and keep the unique ones for further processing.

unique_ticker_symbols <- unique(unlist(strsplit(s_and_p_movements$tickers[1:10], split = ",")))
length(unique_ticker_symbols)
[1] 488

Check Ticker Symbol Availability

We use the TTR package to find out which of those symbols are still commonly available. S&P 500 indizes are usually commonly traded but companies, that do not exist anymore will surely not be listed anymore.

current_common_exchange_symbols <- TTR::stockSymbols()
Fetching NASDAQ symbols...
Fetching non-NASDAQ symbols...
length(current_common_exchange_symbols$Symbol)
[1] 10812

If our symbols arent available anymore we will throw them out.

is_currently_listed <- unique_ticker_symbols %in% current_common_exchange_symbols$Symbol
still_listed_symbols <- unique_ticker_symbols[is_currently_listed]
length(still_listed_symbols)

Collect Ticker Data

We will use the remaining 273 symbols and lookup the daily stock data for them. In the background this will call the Yahoo stock information service. We include all datapoints up to 2021-06-18 and try to go back to 1991 so wed have still a year of data before the dotcom bubble burst.

start_date <- as.Date("1999-01-01")
end_date <- as.Date("2021-06-18")
freqency <- "daily"

lookup_output <- BatchGetSymbols::BatchGetSymbols(tickers = still_listed_symbols,
                                                  first.date = start_date,
                                                  last.date = end_date,
                                                  freq.data = freqency,
                                                  cache.folder = file.path(tempdir(), "BGS_Cache"))

Because we cant sensibly impute data for these financial time series well only include symbols for which there are all price data available.

good_to_go_symbols <- lookup_output$df.control %>%
  filter(perc.benchmark.dates == 1.0) %>%
  (function (x) { x$ticker })

ticker_values <- lookup_output$df.tickers %>%
  filter(ticker %in% good_to_go_symbols) %>%
  as_tsibble(key = ticker, index = ref.date)

ticker_values

Collecting Metadata

For analysis purposes it makes sense to collect additional information like the sector and sub-sector of a company.

good_to_go_meta <- current_common_exchange_symbols %>%
  filter(Symbol %in% good_to_go_symbols)

good_to_go_meta

The SP500_const_info data frame is unfortunately not always up to date so there is a considerable amount of missing data points for our data set. Still, there is enough data to use in our analysis.

additional_meta <- SP500_const_info %>%
  filter(Ticker %in% good_to_go_symbols) %>%
  rename(Symbol = Ticker)

additional_meta

In the end we decided to keep eight attributes in case we need them in further analysis. The most useful of them being the name, the symbol as an identifier, the secotr and the subsector.

complete_meta <- good_to_go_meta %>%
  remove_empty(which = c("cols")) %>%
  select(-c(ACT.Symbol, CQS.Symbol, NASDAQ.Symbol, Test.Issue, ETF)) %>%
  left_join(additional_meta, by = "Symbol")

complete_meta

Quick Sanity Check

At this point we have complete daily time series for 216 ticker symbols. We can plot the daily closing prices for one symbol (AAPL for Apple) to check if the data we pulled down makes sense.

ticker_values %>%
  filter(ticker == "AAPL") %>%
  autoplot(price.close)

Persisting The Data

When were happy with the data we can save it for later processing.

ticker_values %>% write_csv("data/ticker_values.csv")
complete_meta %>% write_csv("data/ticker_meta.csv")
